# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: mesh-processing
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:mesh-processing/delaunay-triangulation] This maximizes the size of the smallest angle in any of the triangles, and tends to avoid sliver triangles.
[src:mesh-processing/delaunay-triangulation] The triangulation is named after Boris Delaunay for his work on it from 1934.
[src:mesh-processing/delaunay-triangulation] If the points all lie on a straight line, the notion of triangulation becomes degenerate and there is no Delaunay triangulation.
[src:mesh-processing/delaunay-triangulation] By considering circumscribed spheres, the notion of Delaunay triangulation extends to three and higher dimensions.
[src:mesh-processing/delaunay-triangulation] Generalizations are possible to metrics other than Euclidean distance.
[src:mesh-processing/delaunay-triangulation] However, in these cases a Delaunay triangulation is not guaranteed to exist or be unique.
[src:mesh-processing/delaunay-triangulation] The Delaunay triangulation with all the circumcircles and their centers (in red).
[src:mesh-processing/delaunay-triangulation] The Delaunay triangulation of a discrete point set **P** in general position corresponds to the dual graph of the Voronoi diagram for **P**.
[src:mesh-processing/delaunay-triangulation] The circumcenters of Delaunay triangles are the vertices of the Voronoi diagram.
[src:mesh-processing/delaunay-triangulation] In the 2D case, the Voronoi vertices are connected via edges, that can be derived from adjacency-relationships of the Delaunay triangles: If two triangles share an edge in the Delaunay triangulation, their circumcenters are to be connected with an edge in the Voronoi tesselation.
[src:mesh-processing/delaunay-triangulation] For a set **P** of points in the (d-dimensional) Euclidean space, a **Delaunay triangulation** is a triangulation DT(**P**) such that no point in **P** is inside the circum-hypersphere of any d-simplex in DT(**P**).
[src:mesh-processing/delaunay-triangulation] It is known that there exists a unique Delaunay triangulation for **P** if **P** is a set of points in *general position*; that is, the affine hull of **P** is d-dimensional and no set of *d* + 2 points in **P** lie on the boundary of a ball whose interior does not intersect **P**.
[src:mesh-processing/delaunay-triangulation] The problem of finding the Delaunay triangulation of a set of points in d-dimensional Euclidean space can be converted to the problem of finding the convex hull of a set of points in (*d* + 1)-dimensional space.
[src:mesh-processing/delaunay-triangulation] As the convex hull is unique, so is the triangulation, assuming all facets of the convex hull are simplices.
[src:mesh-processing/delaunay-triangulation] Nonsimplicial facets only occur when *d* + 2 of the original points lie on the same d-hypersphere, i.e., the points are not in general position.
[src:mesh-processing/delaunay-triangulation] Let n be the number of points and d the number of dimensions.
[src:mesh-processing/delaunay-triangulation] From the above properties an important feature arises: Looking at two triangles △*ABD*, △*BCD* with the common edge BD (see figures), if the sum of the angles α + γ ≤ 180°, the triangles meet the Delaunay condition.
[src:mesh-processing/delaunay-triangulation] This is an important property because it allows the use of a *flipping* technique.
[src:mesh-processing/delaunay-triangulation] This operation is called a *flip*, and can be generalised to three and higher dimensions.
[src:mesh-processing/delaunay-triangulation] Many algorithms for computing Delaunay triangulations rely on fast operations for detecting when a point is within a triangle's circumcircle and an efficient data structure for storing triangles and edges.
[src:mesh-processing/delaunay-triangulation] When A, B, C are sorted in a counterclockwise order, this determinant is positive only if D lies inside the circumcircle.
[src:mesh-processing/delaunay-triangulation] As mentioned above, if a triangle is non-Delaunay, we can flip one of its edges.
[src:mesh-processing/delaunay-triangulation] This leads to a straightforward algorithm: construct any triangulation of the points, and then flip edges until no triangle is non-Delaunay.
[src:mesh-processing/delaunay-triangulation] Unfortunately, this can take Ω(*n*2) edge flips.
[src:mesh-processing/delaunay-triangulation] While this algorithm can be generalised to three and higher dimensions, its convergence is not guaranteed in these cases, as it is conditioned to the connectedness of the underlying flip graph: this graph is connected for two-dimensional sets of points, but may be disconnected in higher dimensions.
[src:mesh-processing/delaunay-triangulation] The most straightforward way of efficiently computing the Delaunay triangulation is to repeatedly add one vertex at a time, retriangulating the affected parts of the graph.
[src:mesh-processing/delaunay-triangulation] When a vertex v is added, we split in three the triangle that contains v, then we apply the flip algorithm.
[src:mesh-processing/delaunay-triangulation] Done naïvely, this will take O(*n*) time: we search through all the triangles to find the one that contains v, then we potentially flip away every triangle.
[src:mesh-processing/delaunay-triangulation] If we insert vertices in random order, it turns out (by a somewhat intricate proof) that each insertion will flip, on average, only O(1) triangles – although sometimes it will flip many more.
[src:mesh-processing/delaunay-triangulation] This still leaves the point location time to improve.
[src:mesh-processing/delaunay-triangulation] We can store the history of the splits and flips performed: each triangle stores a pointer to the two or three triangles that replaced it.
[src:mesh-processing/delaunay-triangulation] To find the triangle that contains v, we start at a root triangle, and follow the pointer that points to a triangle that contains v, until we find a triangle that has not yet been replaced.
[src:mesh-processing/delaunay-triangulation] On average, this will also take O(log *n*) time.
[src:mesh-processing/delaunay-triangulation] Over all vertices, then, this takes O(*n* log *n*) time.
[src:mesh-processing/delaunay-triangulation] While the technique extends to higher dimensions (as proved by Edelsbrunner and Shah), the runtime can be exponential in the dimension even if the final Delaunay triangulation is small.
[src:mesh-processing/delaunay-triangulation] The Bowyer–Watson algorithm provides another approach for incremental construction.
[src:mesh-processing/delaunay-triangulation] It gives an alternative to edge flipping for computing the Delaunay triangles containing a newly inserted vertex.
[src:mesh-processing/delaunay-triangulation] Unfortunately the flipping-based algorithms are generally hard to parallelize, since adding some certain point (e.g. the center point of a wagon wheel) can lead to up to O(*n*) consecutive flips.
[src:mesh-processing/delaunay-triangulation] Blelloch et al. proposed another version of incremental algorithm based on rip-and-tent, which is practical and highly parallelized with polylogarithmic span.
[src:mesh-processing/delaunay-triangulation] A divide and conquer algorithm for triangulations in two dimensions was developed by Lee and Schachter and improved by Guibas and Stolfi and later by Dwyer.
[src:mesh-processing/delaunay-triangulation] In this algorithm, one recursively draws a line to split the vertices into two sets.
[src:mesh-processing/delaunay-triangulation] The Delaunay triangulation is computed for each set, and then the two sets are merged along the splitting line.
[src:mesh-processing/delaunay-triangulation] Using some clever tricks, the merge operation can be done in time O(*n*), so the total running time is O(*n* log *n*).
[src:mesh-processing/delaunay-triangulation] For certain types of point sets, such as a uniform random distribution, by intelligently picking the splitting lines the expected time can be reduced to O(*n* log log *n*) while still maintaining worst-case performance.
[src:mesh-processing/delaunay-triangulation] A divide and conquer paradigm to performing a triangulation in d dimensions is presented in "DeWall: A fast divide and conquer Delaunay triangulation algorithm in E*d*" by P.
[src:mesh-processing/delaunay-triangulation] The divide and conquer algorithm has been shown to be the fastest DT generation technique sequentially.
[src:mesh-processing/delaunay-triangulation] Sweephull is a hybrid technique for 2D Delaunay triangulation that uses a radially propagating sweep-hull, and a flipping algorithm.
[src:mesh-processing/delaunay-triangulation] The sweep-hull is created sequentially by iterating a radially-sorted set of 2D points, and connecting triangles to the visible part of the convex hull, which gives a non-overlapping triangulation.
[src:mesh-processing/delaunay-triangulation] One can build a convex hull in this manner so long as the order of points guarantees no point would fall within the triangle.
[src:mesh-processing/delaunay-triangulation] But, radially sorting should minimize flipping by being highly Delaunay to start.
[src:mesh-processing/delaunay-triangulation] This is then paired with a final iterative triangle flipping step.
[src:mesh-processing/delaunay-triangulation] The Euclidean minimum spanning tree of a set of points is a subset of the Delaunay triangulation of the same points, and this can be exploited to compute it efficiently.
[src:mesh-processing/delaunay-triangulation] For modelling terrain or other objects given a point cloud, the Delaunay triangulation gives a nice set of triangles to use as polygons in the model.
[src:mesh-processing/delaunay-triangulation] In particular, the Delaunay triangulation avoids narrow triangles (as they have large circumcircles compared to their area).
[src:mesh-processing/delaunay-triangulation] Delaunay triangulations can be used to determine the density or intensity of points samplings by means of the Delaunay tessellation field estimator (DTFE).
[src:mesh-processing/delaunay-triangulation] Delaunay triangulations are often used to generate meshes for space-discretised solvers such as the finite element method and the finite volume method of physics simulation, because of the angle guarantee and because fast triangulation algorithms have been developed.
[src:mesh-processing/delaunay-triangulation] Typically, the domain to be meshed is specified as a coarse simplicial complex; for the mesh to be numerically stable, it must be refined, for instance by using Ruppert's algorithm.
[src:mesh-processing/delaunay-triangulation] The increasing popularity of finite element method and boundary element method techniques increases the incentive to improve automatic meshing algorithms.
[src:mesh-processing/delaunay-triangulation] However, all of these algorithms can create distorted and even unusable grid elements.
[src:mesh-processing/delaunay-triangulation] Fortunately, several techniques exist which can take an existing mesh and improve its quality.
[src:mesh-processing/delaunay-triangulation] For example, smoothing (also referred to as mesh refinement) is one such method, which repositions nodes to minimize element distortion.
[src:mesh-processing/delaunay-triangulation] The stretched grid method allows the generation of pseudo-regular meshes that meet the Delaunay criteria easily and quickly in a one-step solution.
[src:mesh-processing/delaunay-triangulation] Constrained Delaunay triangulation has found applications in path planning in automated driving and topographic surveying.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] Applications of geometry processing algorithms already cover a wide range of areas from multimedia, entertainment and classical computer-aided design, to biomedical computing, reverse engineering, and scientific computing.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] Geometry processing is a common research topic at SIGGRAPH, the premier computer graphics academic conference, and the main topic of the annual Symposium on Geometry Processing.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] Geometry processing involves working with a shape, usually in 2D or 3D, although the shape can live in a space of arbitrary dimensions.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] The processing of a shape involves three stages, which is known as its life cycle.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] At its "birth," a shape can be instantiated through one of three methods: a model, a mathematical representation, or a scan.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] After a shape is born, it can be analyzed and edited repeatedly in a cycle.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] This usually involves acquiring different measurements, such as the distances between the points of the shape, the smoothness of the shape, or its Euler characteristic.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] Editing may involve denoising, deforming, or performing rigid transformations.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] At the final stage of the shape's "life," it is consumed.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] This can mean it is consumed by a viewer as a rendered asset in a game or movie, for instance.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] The end of a shape's life can also be defined by a decision about the shape, like whether or not it satisfies some criteria.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] Or it can even be fabricated in the real world, through a method such as 3D printing or laser cutting.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] Like any other shape, the shapes used in geometry processing have properties pertaining to their geometry and topology.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] The geometry of a shape concerns the position of the shape's points in space, tangents, normals, and curvature.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] It also includes the dimension in which the shape lives (ex. $R^{2}$ or $R^{3}$ ).
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] The topology of a shape is a collection of properties that do not change even after smooth transformations have been applied to the shape.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] It concerns dimensions such as the number of holes and boundaries, as well as the orientability of the shape.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] One example of a non-orientable shape is the Mobius strip.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] In computers, everything must be discretized.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] Shapes in geometry processing are usually represented as triangle meshes, which can be seen as a graph.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] Each node in the graph is a vertex (usually in $R^{3}$ ), which has a position.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] Directed edges connect these vertices into triangles, which by the right hand rule, then have a direction called the normal.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] These are combinatoric in nature and encode the topology of the shape.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] In addition to triangles, a more general class of polygon meshes can also be used to represent a shape.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] More advanced representations like progressive meshes encode a coarse representation along with a sequence of transformations, which produce a fine or high resolution representation of the shape once applied.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] These meshes are useful in a variety of applications, including geomorphs, progressive transmission, mesh compression, and selective refinement.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] One particularly important property of a 3D shape is its Euler characteristic, which can alternatively be defined in terms of its genus.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] The formula for this in the continuous sense is $\chi =2c-2h-b$ , where c is the number of connected components, h is number of holes (as in donut holes, see torus), and b is the number of connected components of the boundary of the surface.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] A concrete example of this is a mesh of a pair of pants.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] There is one connected component, 0 holes, and 3 connected components of the boundary (the waist and two leg holes).
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] So in this case, the Euler characteristic is -1.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] To bring this into the discrete world, the Euler characteristic of a mesh is computed in terms of its vertices, edges, and faces. $\chi =|V|-|E|+|F|$ .
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] Depending on how a shape is initialized or "birthed," the shape might exist only as a nebula of sampled points that represent its surface in space.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] To transform the surface points into a mesh, the Poisson reconstruction strategy can be employed.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] This method states that the indicator function, a function that determines which points in space belong to the surface of the shape, can actually be computed from the sampled points.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] The key concept is that gradient of the indicator function is *0* everywhere, except at the sampled points, where it is equal to the inward surface normal.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] More formally, suppose the collection of sampled points from the surface is denoted by S , each point in the space by $p_{i}$ , and the corresponding normal at that point by $n_{i}$ .
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] The task of reconstruction then becomes a variational problem.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] To find the indicator function of the surface, we must find a function $\chi$ such that $\lVert \triangledown \chi -{\textbf {V}}\rVert$ is minimized, where ${\textbf {V}}$ is the vector field defined by the samples.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] As a variational problem, one can view the minimizer $\chi$ as a solution of Poisson's equation.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] An animation depicting the same registration procedure as above, but with piecewise linear approximation of the projection function.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] One common problem encountered in geometry processing is how to merge multiple views of a single object captured from different angles or positions.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] In registration, we wish to find an optimal rigid transformation that will align surface X with surface Y .
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] While rotations are non-linear in general, small rotations can be linearized as skew-symmetric matrices.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] Moreover, the distance function $x-P_{Y}(x)$ is non-linear, but is amenable to linear approximations if the change in X is small.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] An iterative solution such as Iterative Closest Point (ICP) is therefore employed to solve for small transformations iteratively, instead of solving for the potentially large transformation in one go.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] In ICP, *n* random sample points from X are chosen and projected onto Y .
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] Thereafter, the optimal transformation is calculated based on the difference between each x and its projection.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] In the following iteration, the projections are calculated based on the result of applying the previous transformation on the samples.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] The process is repeated until convergence.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] When shapes are defined or scanned, there may be accompanying noise, either to a signal acting upon the surface or to the actual surface geometry.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] Reducing noise on the former is known as data denoising, while noise reduction on the latter is known as surface fairing.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] The task of geometric smoothing is analogous to signal noise reduction, and consequently employs similar approaches.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] where our choice of $\nabla ^{2}$ is chosen to be $M^{-1}\mathbf {L}$ for the cotangent Laplacian $\mathbf {L}$ and the $M^{-1}$ term is to map the image of the Laplacian from areas to points.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] Occasionally, we need to flatten a 3D surface onto a flat plane.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] This process is known as parameterization.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] The goal is to find coordinates *u* and *v* onto which we can map the surface so that distortions are minimized.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] In this manner, parameterization can be seen as an optimization problem.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] One of the major applications of mesh parameterization is texture mapping.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] One way to measure the distortion accrued in the mapping process is to measure how much the length of the edges on the 2D mapping differs from their lengths in the original 3D surface.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] Where E is the set of mesh edges and U is the set of vertices.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] However, optimizing this objective function would result in a solution that maps all of the vertices to a single vertex in the *uv*-coordinates.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] Borrowing an idea from graph theory, we apply the Tutte Mapping and restrict the boundary vertices of the mesh onto a unit circle or other convex polygon.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] Doing so prevents the vertices from collapsing into a single vertex when the mapping is applied.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] The non-boundary vertices are then positioned at the barycentric interpolation of their neighbours.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] The Tutte Mapping, however, still suffers from severe distortions as it attempts to make the edge lengths equal, and hence does not correctly account for the triangle sizes on the actual surface mesh.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] Another way to measure the distortion is to consider the variations on the *u* and *v* coordinate functions.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] The wobbliness and distortion apparent in the mass springs methods are due to high variations in the *u* and *v* coordinate functions.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] There are a few other things to consider.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] We would like to minimize the angle distortion to preserve orthogonality.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] That means we would like $\nabla u=\nabla v^{\perp }$ .
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] In addition, we would also like the mapping to have proportionally similar sized regions as the original.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] This results to setting the Jacobian of the *u* and *v* coordinate functions to 1.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] To avoid the problem of having all the vertices mapped to a single point, we also require that the solution to the optimization problem must have a non-zero norm and that it is orthogonal to the trivial solution.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] Deformation is concerned with transforming some rest shape to a new shape.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] Typically, these transformations are continuous and do not alter the topology of the shape.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] Modern mesh-based shape deformation methods satisfy user deformation constraints at handles (selected vertices or regions on the mesh) and propagate these handle deformations to the rest of shape smoothly and without removing or distorting details.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] Some common forms of interactive deformations are point-based, skeleton-based, and cage-based.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] In point-based deformation, a user can apply transformations to small set of points, called handles, on the shape.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] Skeleton-based deformation defines a skeleton for the shape, which allows a user to move the bones and rotate the joints.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] Cage-based deformation requires a cage to be drawn around all or part of a shape so that, when the user manipulates points on the cage, the volume it encloses changes accordingly.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] Handles provide a sparse set of constraints for the deformation: as the user moves one point, the others must stay in place.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] A rest surface ${\hat {S}}$ immersed in $\mathbb {R} ^{3}$ can be described with a mapping ${\hat {x}}:\Omega \rightarrow \mathbb {R} ^{3}$ , where $\Omega$ is a 2D parametric domain.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] The same can be done with another mapping x for the transformed surface S .
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] Ideally, the transformed shape adds as little distortion as possible to the original.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] One way to model this distortion is in terms of displacements $d=x-{\hat {x}}$ with a Laplacian-based energy.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] Applying the Laplace operator to these mappings allows us to measure how the position of a point changes relative to its neighborhood, which keeps the handles smooth.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] While this method is translation invariant, it is unable to account for rotations.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] The As-Rigid-As-Possible deformation scheme applies a rigid transformation $x_{i}=R{\hat {x_{i}}}+t$ to each handle i, where $R\in SO(3)\subset \mathbb {R} ^{3}$ is a rotation matrix and $t\in \mathbb {R} ^{3}$ is a translation vector.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] Unfortunately, there's no way to know the rotations in advance, so instead we pick a “best” rotation that minimizes displacements.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] To achieve local rotation invariance, however, requires a function ${\textbf {R}}:\Omega \rightarrow SO(3)$ which outputs the best rotation for every point on the surface.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] Note that the translation vector is not present in the final objective function because translations have constant gradient.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] While seemingly trivial, in many cases, determining the inside from the outside of a triangle mesh is not an easy problem.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] In general, given a surface S we pose this problem as determining a function $isInside(q)$ which will return 1 if the point q is inside S , and 0 otherwise.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] In the simplest case, the shape is closed.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] In this case, to determine if a point q is inside or outside the surface, we can cast a ray r in any direction from a query point, and count the number of times $count_{r}$ it passes through the surface.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] If q was outside S then the ray must either not pass through S (in which case $count_{r}=0$ ) or, each time it enters S it must pass through twice, because S is bounded, so any ray entering it must exit.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] So if q is outside, $count_{r}$ is even.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] Likewise if q is inside, the same logic applies to the previous case, but the ray must intersect S one extra time for the first time it leaves S .
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] Now, oftentimes we cannot guarantee that the S is closed.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] Take the pair of pants example from the top of this article.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] This mesh clearly has a semantic inside-and-outside, despite there being holes at the waist and the legs.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] The naive attempt to solve this problem is to shoot many rays in random directions, and classify q as being inside if and only if most of the rays intersected S an odd number of times.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] To quantify this, let us say we cast k rays, $r_{1},r_{2},\dots ,r_{k}$ .
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] We associate a number $rayTest(q)={\frac {1}{k}}\sum _{i=1}^{k}isInside_{r_{i}}(q)$ which is the average value of $isInside_{r}$ from each ray.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] In the limit of shooting many, many rays, this method handles open meshes, however it in order to become accurate, far too many rays are required for this method to be computationally ideal.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] Instead, a more robust approach is the Generalized Winding Number.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] Inspired by the 2D winding number, this approach uses the solid angle at q of each triangle in the mesh to determine if q is inside or outside.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] For a closed mesh, $wn(q)$ is equivalent to the characteristic function for the volume represented by S .
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] Because $wn(q)$ is a harmonic function, it degrades gracefully, meaning the inside-outside segmentation would not change much if we poked holes in a closed mesh.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] For this reason, the Generalized Winding Number handles open meshes robustly.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] The boundary between inside and outside smoothly passes over holes in the mesh.
[src:mesh-processing/geometry-processing] In fact, in the limit, the Generalized Winding Number is equivalent to the ray-casting method as the number of rays goes to infinity.
[src:mesh-processing/marching-cubes] The algorithm was developed by William E.
[src:mesh-processing/marching-cubes] Cline as a result of their research for General Electric.
[src:mesh-processing/marching-cubes] At General Electric they worked on a way to efficiently visualize data from CT and MRI devices.
[src:mesh-processing/marching-cubes] The premise of the algorithm is to divide the input volume into a discrete set of cubes.
[src:mesh-processing/marching-cubes] By assuming linear reconstruction filtering, each cube, which contains a piece of a given isosurface, can easily be identified because the sample values at the cube vertices must span the target isosurface value.
[src:mesh-processing/marching-cubes] For each cube containing a section of the isosurface, a triangular mesh that approximates the behavior of the trilinear interpolant in the interior cube is generated.
[src:mesh-processing/marching-cubes] The first published version of the algorithm exploited rotational and reflective symmetry and also sign changes to build the table with 15 unique cases.
[src:mesh-processing/marching-cubes] However, due to the existence of ambiguities in the trilinear interpolant behavior in the cube faces and interior, the meshes extracted by the Marching Cubes presented discontinuities and topological issues.
[src:mesh-processing/marching-cubes] Given a cube of the grid, a face ambiguity occurs when its face vertices have alternating signs.
[src:mesh-processing/marching-cubes] That is, the vertices of one diagonal on this face are positive and the vertices on the other are negative.
[src:mesh-processing/marching-cubes] Observe that in this case, the signs of the face vertices are insufficient to determine the correct way to triangulate the isosurface.
[src:mesh-processing/marching-cubes] Similarly, an interior ambiguity occurs when the signs of the cube vertices are insufficient to determine the correct surface triangulation, i.e., when multiple triangulations are possible for the same cube configuration.
[src:mesh-processing/marching-cubes] The popularity of the Marching Cubes and its widespread adoption resulted in several improvements in the algorithm to deal with the ambiguities and to correctly track the behavior of the interpolant.
[src:mesh-processing/marching-cubes] Durst in 1988 was the first to note that the triangulation table proposed by Lorensen and Cline was incomplete, and that certain Marching Cubes cases allow multiple triangulations.
[src:mesh-processing/marching-cubes] Durst's 'additional reference' was to an earlier, more efficient (see de Araujo) isosurface polygonization algorithm by Wyvill, Wyvill and McPheeters.
[src:mesh-processing/marching-cubes] Later, Nielson and Hamann in 1991 observed the existence of ambiguities in the interpolant behavior on the face of the cube.
[src:mesh-processing/marching-cubes] They proposed a test called Asymptotic Decider to correctly track the interpolant on the faces of the cube.
[src:mesh-processing/marching-cubes] In fact, as observed by Natarajan in 1994, this ambiguity problem also occurs inside the cube.
[src:mesh-processing/marching-cubes] In his work, the author proposed a disambiguation test based on the interpolant critical points, and added four new cases to the Marching Cubes triangulation table (subcases of the cases 3, 4, 6 and 7).
[src:mesh-processing/marching-cubes] At this point, even with all the improvements proposed to the algorithm and its triangulation table, the meshes generated by the Marching Cubes still had topological incoherencies.
[src:mesh-processing/marching-cubes] The Marching Cubes 33, proposed by Chernyaev in 1995, is one of the first isosurface extraction algorithms intended to preserve the topology of the trilinear interpolant.
[src:mesh-processing/marching-cubes] In his work, Chernyaev extends to 33 the number of cases in the triangulation lookup table.
[src:mesh-processing/marching-cubes] He then proposes a different approach to solve the interior ambiguities, which is based on the Asymptotic Decider.
[src:mesh-processing/marching-cubes] Later, in 2003, Nielson proved that Chernyaev's lookup table is complete and can represent all the possible behaviors of the trilinear interpolant, and Lewiner et al. proposed an implementation to the algorithm.
[src:mesh-processing/marching-cubes] Also in 2003 Lopes and Brodlie extended the tests proposed by Natarajan.
[src:mesh-processing/marching-cubes] In 2013, Custodio et al. noted and corrected algorithmic inaccuracies that compromised the topological correctness of the mesh generated by the Marching Cubes 33 algorithm proposed by Chernyaev.
[src:mesh-processing/marching-cubes] The algorithm proceeds through the scalar field, taking eight neighbor locations at a time (thus forming an imaginary cube), then determining the polygon(s) needed to represent the part of the isosurface that passes through this cube.
[src:mesh-processing/marching-cubes] The individual polygons are then fused into the desired surface.
[src:mesh-processing/marching-cubes] This is done by creating an index to a precalculated array of 256 possible polygon configurations (28=256) within the cube, by treating each of the 8 scalar values as a bit in an 8-bit integer.
[src:mesh-processing/marching-cubes] If the scalar's value is higher than the iso-value (i.e., it is inside the surface) then the appropriate bit is set to one, while if it is lower (outside), it is set to zero.
[src:mesh-processing/marching-cubes] The final value, after all eight scalars are checked, is the actual index to the polygon indices array.
[src:mesh-processing/marching-cubes] Finally each vertex of the generated polygons is placed on the appropriate position along the cube's edge by linearly interpolating the two scalar values that are connected by that edge.
[src:mesh-processing/marching-cubes] The gradient of the scalar field at each grid point is also the normal vector of a hypothetical isosurface passing from that point.
[src:mesh-processing/marching-cubes] Therefore, these normals may be interpolated along the edges of each cube to find the normals of the generated vertices which are essential for shading the resulting mesh with some illumination model.
[src:mesh-processing/marching-cubes] An implementation of the marching cubes algorithm was patented as United States Patent 4,710,876.
[src:mesh-processing/marching-cubes] Another similar algorithm was developed, called marching tetrahedra, in order to circumvent the patent as well as solve a minor ambiguity problem of marching cubes with some cube configurations.
[src:mesh-processing/marching-cubes] The patent expired in 2005, and it is now legal for the graphics community to use it without royalties since more than the 20 years have passed from its issue date (December 1, 1987).
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] Meshes are used for rendering to a computer screen and for physical simulation such as finite element analysis or computational fluid dynamics.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] We can simulate the strength of the bridge, or draw it on a computer screen, by performing calculations on each triangle and calculating the interactions between triangles.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] A major distinction is between structured and unstructured meshing.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] In structured meshing the mesh is a regular lattice, such as an array, with implied connectivity between elements.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] In unstructured meshing, elements may be connected to each other in irregular patterns, and more complicated domains can be captured.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] This page is primarily about unstructured meshes.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] While a mesh may be a triangulation, the process of meshing is distinguished from point set triangulation in that meshing includes the freedom to add vertices not present in the input.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] "Facetting" (triangulating) CAD models for drafting has the same freedom to add vertices, but the goal is to represent the shape accurately using as few triangles as possible and the shape of individual triangles is not important.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] Computer graphics renderings of textures and realistic lighting conditions use meshes instead.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] Many mesh generation software is coupled to a CAD system defining its input, and simulation software for taking its output.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] The input can vary greatly but common forms are Solid modeling, Geometric modeling, NURBS, B-rep, STL or a point cloud.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] Mesh faces (cells, entities) have different names depending on their dimension and the context in which the mesh will be used.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] In finite elements, the highest-dimensional mesh entities are called "elements," "edges" are 1D and "nodes" are 0D.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] If the elements are 3D, then the 2D entities are "faces." In computational geometry, the 0D points are called vertices.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] Many meshing techniques are built on the principles of the Delaunay triangulation, together with rules for adding vertices, such as Ruppert's algorithm.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] A distinguishing feature is that an initial coarse mesh of the entire space is formed, then vertices and triangles are added.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] In contrast, advancing front algorithms start from the domain boundary, and add elements incrementally filling up the interior.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] A special class of advancing front techniques creates thin boundary layers of elements for fluid flow.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] In structured mesh generation the entire mesh is a lattice graph, such as a regular grid of squares.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] In block-structured meshing, the domain is divided into large subregions, each of which is a structured mesh.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] Some direct methods start with a block-structured mesh and then move the mesh to conform to the input; see Automatic Hex-Mesh Generation based on polycube.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] Another direct method is to cut the structured cells by the domain boundary; see sculpt based on Marching cubes.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] Some types of meshes are much more difficult to create than others.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] Simplicial meshes tend to be easier than cubical meshes.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] An important category is generating a hex mesh conforming to a fixed quad surface mesh; a research subarea is studying the existence and generation of meshes of specific small configurations, such as the tetragonal trapezohedron.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] Because of the difficulty of this problem, the existence of combinatorial hex meshes has been studied apart from the problem of generating good geometric realizations; see Combinatorial Techniques for Hexahedral Mesh Generation.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] While known algorithms generate simplicial meshes with guaranteed minimum quality, such guarantees are rare for cubical meshes, and many popular implementations generate inverted (inside-out) hexes from some inputs.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] Meshes are often created in serial on workstations, even when subsequent calculations over the mesh will be done in parallel on super-computers.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] This is both because of the limitation that most mesh generators are interactive, and because mesh generation runtime is typically insignificant compared to solver time.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] However, if the mesh is too large to fit in the memory of a single serial machine, or the mesh must be changed (adapted) during the simulation, meshing is done in parallel.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] The grid generation by algebraic methods is based on mathematical interpolation function.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] It is done by using known functions in one, two or three dimensions taking arbitrary shaped regions.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] The computational domain might not be rectangular, but for the sake of simplicity, the domain is taken to be rectangular.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] The main advantage of the methods is that they provide explicit control of physical grid shape and spacing.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] The simplest procedure that may be used to produce boundary fitted computational mesh is the normalization transformation.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] where $y_{\max }$ denotes the y-coordinate of the nozzle wall.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] For given values of ( $\xi$ , $\eta$ ), the values of ( x , y ) can be easily recovered.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] Like algebraic methods, differential equation methods are also used to generate grids.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] The advantage of using the partial differential equations (PDEs) is that the solution of grid generating equations can be exploited to generate the mesh.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] Grid construction can be done using all three classes of partial differential equations.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] Elliptic PDEs generally have very smooth solutions leading to smooth contours.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] Using its smoothness as an advantage Laplace's equations can preferably be used because the Jacobian found out to be positive as a result of maximum principle for harmonic functions.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] After extensive work done by Crowley (1962) and Winslow (1966) on PDEs by transforming physical domain into computational plane while mapping using Poisson's equation, Thompson et al.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] (1974) have worked extensively on elliptic PDEs to generate grids.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] where, $(\xi ,\eta )$ are the co-ordinates in the computational domain, while P and Q are responsible for point spacing within D.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] These systems of equations are solved in the computational plane on uniformly spaced grid which provides us with the $(x,y)$ co-ordinates of each point in physical space.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] The advantage of using elliptic PDEs is the solution linked to them is smooth and the resulting grid is smooth.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] But, specification of P and Q becomes a difficult task thus adding it to its disadvantages.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] Moreover, the grid has to be computed after each time step which adds up to computational time.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] This grid generation scheme is generally applicable to problems with open domains consistent with the type of PDE describing the physical problem.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] The advantage associated with hyperbolic PDEs is that the governing equations need to be solved only once for generating grid.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] The initial point distribution along with the approximate boundary conditions forms the required input and the solution is the then marched outward.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] Steger and Sorenson (1980) proposed a volume orthogonality method that uses Hyperbolic PDEs for mesh generation.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] where I represents the area in physical space for a given area in computational space.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] The problem associated with such system of equations is the specification of I .
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] Poor selection of I may lead to shock and discontinuous propagation of this information throughout the mesh.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] While mesh being orthogonal is generated very rapidly which comes out as an advantage with this method.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] The solving technique is similar to that of hyperbolic PDEs by advancing the solution away from the initial data surface satisfying the boundary conditions at the end.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] Nakamura (1982) and Edwards (1985) developed the basic ideas for parabolic grid generation.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] The idea uses either of Laplace or the Poisson's equation and especially treating the parts which controls elliptic behavior.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] The initial values are given as the coordinates of the point along the surface $\eta =0$ and the advancing the solutions to the outer surface of the object satisfying the boundary conditions along $\xi$ edges.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] The control of the grid spacing has not been suggested until now.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] Nakamura and Edwards, grid control was accomplished using non uniform spacing.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] The parabolic grid generation shows an advantage over the hyperbolic grid generation that, no shocks or discontinuities occur and the grid is relatively smooth.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] The specifications of initial values and selection of step size to control the grid points is however time-consuming, but these techniques can be effective when familiarity and experience is gained.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] This method includes a technique that minimizes grid smoothness, orthogonality and volume variation.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] This method forms mathematical platform to solve grid generation problems.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] In this method an alternative grid is generated by a new mesh after each iteration and computing the grid speed using backward difference method.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] This technique is a powerful one with a disadvantage that effort is required to solve the equations related to grid.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] Further work needed to be done to minimize the integrals that will reduce the CPU time.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] The main importance of this scheme is that it provides a method that will generate the grid automatically.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] Using this method, grids are segmented into blocks according to the surface of the element and a structure is provided to ensure appropriate connectivity.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] To interpret the data flow solver is used.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] When an unstructured scheme is employed, the main interest is to fulfill the demand of the user and a grid generator is used to accomplish this task.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] The information storage in structured scheme is cell to cell instead of grid to grid and hence the more memory space is needed.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] Due to random cell location, the solver efficiency in unstructured is less as compared to the structured scheme.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] Some points are needed to be kept in mind at the time of grid construction.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] The grid point with high resolution creates difficulty for both structured and unstructured.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] For example, in case of boundary layer, structured scheme produces elongated grid in the direction of flow.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] On the other hand, unstructured grids require a higher cell density in the boundary layer because the cell needs to be as equilateral as possible to avoid errors.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] We must identify what information is required to identify the cell and all the neighbors of the cell in the computational mesh.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] We can choose to locate the arbitrary points anywhere we want for the unstructured grid.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] A point insertion scheme is used to insert the points independently and the cell connectivity is determined.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] This suggests that the point be identified as they are inserted.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] Logic for establishing new connectivity is determined once the points are inserted.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] Data that form grid point that identifies grid cell are needed.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] As each cell is formed it is numbered and the points are sorted.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] In addition the neighbor cell information is needed.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] A problem in solving partial differential equations using previous methods is that the grid is constructed and the points are distributed in the physical domain before details of the solution is known.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] So the grid may or may not be the best for the given problem.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] Adaptive methods are used to improve the accuracy of the solutions.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] The adaptive method is referred to as ‘h’ method if mesh refinement is used, ‘r’ method if the number of grid point is fixed and not redistributed and ‘p’ if the order of solution scheme is increased in finite-element theory.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] The multi dimensional problems using the equidistribution scheme can be accomplished in several ways.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] The simplest to understand are the Poisson Grid Generators with control function based on the equidistribution of the weight function with the diffusion set as a multiple of desired cell volume.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] The equidistribution scheme can also be applied to the unstructured problem.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] The problem is the connectivity hampers if mesh point movement is very large.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] Steady flow and the time-accurate flow calculation can be solved through this adaptive method.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] The grid is refined and after a predetermined number of iteration in order to adapt it in a steady flow problem.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] The grid will stop adjusting to the changes once the solution converges.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] In time accurate case coupling of the partial differential equations of the physical problem and those describing the grid movement is required.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] Image-based meshing is the automated process of creating computer models for computational fluid dynamics (CFD) and finite element analysis (FEA) from 3D image data (such as magnetic resonance imaging (MRI), computed tomography (CT) or microtomography).
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] Although a wide range of mesh generation techniques are currently available, these were usually developed to generate models from computer-aided design (CAD), and therefore have difficulties meshing from 3D imaging data.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] Recent advances in artificial intelligence (AI) and machine learning (ML) have significantly impacted mesh generation, automating traditionally labor-intensive processes and improving accuracy in computational simulations.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] AI-driven techniques, such as neural networks and reinforcement learning, can predict optimal mesh configurations, adaptively refine meshes, and reduce manual intervention in finite element analysis (FEA) and computational fluid dynamics (CFD).
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] Companies like NVIDIA, Ansys, and Siemens have integrated AI-based mesh generation tools into their simulation software, accelerating workflows in aerospace, automotive, and biomedical engineering.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] Usually the cells are polygonal or polyhedral and form a mesh that partitions the domain.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] Important classes of two-dimensional elements include triangles (simplices) and quadrilaterals (topological squares).
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] In three-dimensions the most-common cells are tetrahedra (simplices) and hexahedra (topological cubes).
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] Simplicial meshes may be of any dimension and include triangles (2D) and tetrahedra (3D) as important instances.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] *Cubical meshes* is the pan-dimensional category that includes quads (2D) and hexes (3D).
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] In 3D, 4-sided pyramids and 3-sided prisms appear in conformal meshes of mixed cell type.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] The mesh is embedded in a geometric space that is typically two or three dimensional, although sometimes the dimension is increased by one by adding the time-dimension.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] Higher dimensional meshes are used in niche contexts.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] One-dimensional meshes are useful as well.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] A significant category is surface meshes, which are 2D meshes embedded in 3D to represent a curved surface.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] Dual graphs have several roles in meshing.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] One can make a polyhedral Voronoi diagram mesh by dualizing a Delaunay triangulation simplicial mesh.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] One can create a cubical mesh by generating an arrangement of surfaces and dualizing the intersection graph; see spatial twist continuum.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] Sometimes both the primal mesh and its dual mesh are used in the same simulation; see Hodge star operator.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] This arises from physics involving divergence and curl operators, such as flux and vorticity or electricity & magnetism, where one variable naturally lives on the primal faces and its counterpart on the dual faces.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] Three-dimensional meshes created for finite element analysis need to consist of tetrahedra, pyramids, prisms or hexahedra.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] Those used for the finite volume method can consist of arbitrary polyhedra.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] Those used for finite difference methods consist of piecewise structured arrays of hexahedra known as multi-block structured meshes.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] 4-sided pyramids are useful to conformally connect hexes to tets.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] 3-sided prisms are used for boundary layers conforming to a tet mesh of the far-interior of the object.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] Surface meshes are useful in computer graphics where the surfaces of objects reflect light (also subsurface scattering) and a full 3D mesh is not needed.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] Surface meshes are also used to model thin objects such as sheet metal in auto manufacturing and building exteriors in architecture.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] High (e.g., 17) dimensional cubical meshes are common in astrophysics and string theory.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] What is the precise definition of a *mesh?* There is not a universally-accepted mathematical description that applies in all contexts.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] However, some mathematical objects are clearly meshes: a simplicial complex is a mesh composed of simplices.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] Most polyhedral (e.g. cubical) meshes are *conformal,* meaning they have the cell structure of a CW complex, a generalization of a simplicial complex.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] A mesh need not be simplicial because an arbitrary subset of nodes of a cell is not necessarily a cell: e.g., three nodes of a quad does not define a cell.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] However, two cells intersect at cells: e.g. a quad does not have a node in its interior.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] The intersection of two cells may be several cells: e.g., two quads may share two edges.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] An intersection being more than one cell is sometimes forbidden and rarely desired; the goal of some mesh improvement techniques (e.g. pillowing) is to remove these configurations.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] In some contexts, a distinction is made between a topological mesh and a geometric mesh whose embedding satisfies certain quality criteria.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] Important mesh variants that are not CW complexes include non-conformal meshes where cells do not meet strictly face-to-face, but the cells nonetheless partition the domain.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] An example of this is an octree, where an element face may be partitioned by the faces of adjacent elements.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] Such meshes are useful for flux-based simulations.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] In overset grids, there are multiple conformal meshes that overlap geometrically and do not partition the domain; see e.g., Overflow, the OVERset grid FLOW solver.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] So-called meshless or meshfree methods often make use of some mesh-like discretization of the domain, and have basis functions with overlapping support.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] Sometimes a local mesh is created near each simulation degree-of-freedom point, and these meshes may overlap and be non-conformal to one another.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] Implicit triangulations are based on a delta complex: for each triangle the lengths of its edges, and a gluing map between face edges.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] Many meshes use linear elements, where the mapping from the abstract to realized element is linear, and mesh edges are straight segments.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] Higher order polynomial mappings are common, especially quadratic.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] A primary goal for higher-order elements is to more accurately represent the domain boundary, although they have accuracy benefits in the interior of the mesh as well.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] One of the motivations for cubical meshes is that linear cubical elements have some of the same numerical advantages as quadratic simplicial elements.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] In the isogeometric analysis simulation technique, the mesh cells containing the domain boundary use the CAD representation directly instead of a linear or polynomial approximation.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] Improving a mesh involves changing its discrete connectivity, the continuous geometric position of its cells, or both.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] For discrete changes, for simplicial elements one swaps edges and inserts/removes nodes.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] The same kinds of operations are done for cubical (quad/hex) meshes, although there are fewer possible operations and local changes have global consequences.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] E.g., for a hexahedral mesh, merging two nodes creates cells that are not hexes, but if diagonally-opposite nodes on a quadrilateral are merged and this is propagated into collapsing an entire face-connected column of hexes, then all remaining cells will still be hexes.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] In adaptive mesh refinement, elements are split (h-refinement) in areas where the function being calculated has a high gradient.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] Meshes are also coarsened, removing elements for efficiency.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] The multigrid method does something similar to refinement and coarsening to speed up the numerical solve, but without actually changing the mesh.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] For continuous changes, nodes are moved, or the higher-dimensional faces are moved by changing the polynomial order of elements.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] Moving nodes to improve quality is called "smoothing" or "r-refinement" and increasing the order of elements is called "p-refinement." Nodes are also moved in simulations where the shape of objects change over time.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] This degrades the shape of the elements.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] If the object deforms enough, the entire object is remeshed and the current solution mapped from the old mesh to the new mesh.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] The field is highly interdisciplinary, with contributions found in mathematics, computer science, and engineering.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] Meshing R&D is distinguished by an equal focus on discrete and continuous math and computation, as with computational geometry, but in contrast to graph theory (discrete) and numerical analysis (continuous).
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] Mesh generation is deceptively difficult: it is easy for humans to see how to create a mesh of a given object, but difficult to program a computer to make good decisions for arbitrary input a priori.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] There is an infinite variety of geometry found in nature and man-made objects.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] Many mesh generation researchers were first users of meshes.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] Mesh generation continues to receive widespread attention, support and funding because the human-time to create a mesh dwarfs the time to set up and solve the calculation once the mesh is finished.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] Meshing research is published in a broad range of journals.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] This is in keeping with the interdisciplinary nature of the research required to make progress, and also the wide variety of applications that make use of meshes.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] About 150 meshing publications appear each year across 20 journals, with at most 20 publications appearing in any one journal.
[src:mesh-processing/mesh-generation] There is no journal whose primary topic is meshing.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] In 3D computer graphics and solid modeling, a **polygon mesh** is a collection of **vertices**, **edges** and **faces** that define the shape of a polyhedral object's surface.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] It simplifies rendering, as in a wire-frame model.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] The faces usually consist of triangles (triangle mesh), quadrilaterals (quads), or other simple convex polygons (n-gons).
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] A polygonal mesh may also be more generally composed of concave polygons, or even polygons with holes.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] The study of polygon meshes is a large sub-field of computer graphics (specifically 3D computer graphics) and geometric modeling.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] Different representations of polygon meshes are used for different applications and goals.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] The variety of operations performed on meshes includes Boolean logic (Constructive solid geometry), smoothing, and simplification.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] Algorithms also exist for ray tracing, collision detection, and rigid-body dynamics with polygon meshes.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] If the mesh's edges are rendered instead of the faces, then the model becomes a wireframe model.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] Several methods exist for mesh generation, including the marching cubes algorithm.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] Volumetric meshes are distinct from polygon meshes in that they explicitly represent both the surface and interior region of a structure, while polygon meshes only explicitly represent the surface (the volume is implicit).
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] Objects created with polygon meshes must store different types of elements.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] These include vertices, edges, faces, polygons and surfaces.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] In many applications, only vertices, edges and either faces or polygons are stored.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] A renderer may support only 3-sided faces, so polygons must be constructed of many of these, as shown above.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] However, many renderers either support quads and higher-sided polygons, or are able to convert polygons to triangles on the fly, making it unnecessary to store a mesh in a triangulated form.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] A vertex in computer graphics terms is a data structure that describes the position of a point in 2, 3 or 4D space on a surface along with optional attributes - other values used to render the object correctly.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] Most attributes of a vertex represent vectors in the space to be rendered.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] These vectors are typically 2 (*x, y*) or 3 (*x, y, z*) dimensional and can include a fourth homogeneous coordinate (*w*)..
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] In real-time rendering these properties are used by a vertex shader or vertex pipeline.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] Attributes can include position, color, reflectance, specularity, texture mapping coordinates, normal vectors, and displacement mapping.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] Polygon meshes may be represented in a variety of ways, using different methods to store the vertex, edge and face data.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] Each representation has advantages and disadvantages, discussed in Smith (2006).
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] Vertex-vertex meshes represent an object as a set of vertices connected to other vertices.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] This is the simplest representation, but not widely used since the face and edge information is implicit.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] Thus, it is necessary to traverse the data in order to generate a list of faces for rendering.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] In addition, operations on edges and faces are not easily accomplished.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] However, VV meshes benefit from small storage space and efficient morphing of shape.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] The above figure shows a four-sided box as represented by a VV mesh.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] Each vertex indexes its neighboring vertices.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] The last two vertices, 8 and 9 at the top and bottom center of the "box-cylinder", have four connected vertices rather than five.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] A general system must be able to handle an arbitrary number of vertices connected to any given vertex.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] For a complete description of VV meshes see Smith (2006).
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] Face-vertex meshes represent an object as a set of faces and a set of vertices.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] This is the most widely used mesh representation, being the input typically accepted by modern graphics hardware.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] Face-vertex meshes improve on VV mesh for modelling in that they allow explicit lookup of the vertices of a face, and the faces surrounding a vertex.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] The above figure shows the "box-cylinder" example as an FV mesh.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] Vertex v5 is highlighted to show the faces that surround it.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] Notice that, in this example, every face is required to have exactly 3 vertices.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] However, this does not mean every vertex has the same number of surrounding faces.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] For rendering, the face list is usually transmitted to the GPU as a set of indices to vertices, and the vertices are sent as position/color/normal structures (in the figure, only position is given).
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] This has the benefit that changes in shape, but not geometry, can be dynamically updated by simply resending the vertex data without updating the face connectivity.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] Modelling requires easy traversal of all structures.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] With face-vertex meshes it is easy to find the vertices of a face.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] Also, the vertex list contains a list of faces connected to each vertex.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] Unlike VV meshes, both faces and vertices are explicit, so locating neighboring faces and vertices is constant time.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] However, the edges are implicit, so a search is still needed to find all the faces surrounding a given face.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] Other dynamic operations, such as splitting or merging a face, are also difficult with face-vertex meshes.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] Introduced by Baumgart in 1975, winged-edge meshes explicitly represent the vertices, faces, and edges of a mesh.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] This representation is widely used in modelling programs to provide the greatest flexibility in dynamically changing the mesh geometry, because split and merge operations can be done quickly.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] Their primary drawback is large storage requirements and increased complexity due to maintaining many indices.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] A good discussion of implementation issues of Winged-edge meshes may be found in the book *Graphics Gems II*.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] Winged-edge meshes address the issue of traversing from edge to edge, and providing an ordered set of faces around an edge.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] For any given edge, the number of outgoing edges may be arbitrary.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] To simplify this, winged-edge meshes provide only four, the nearest clockwise and counter-clockwise edges at each end.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] The other edges may be traversed incrementally.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] The information for each edge therefore resembles a butterfly, hence "winged-edge" meshes.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] The above figure shows the "box-cylinder" as a winged-edge mesh.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] The total data for an edge consists of 2 vertices (endpoints), 2 faces (on each side), and 4 edges (winged-edge).
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] Rendering of winged-edge meshes for graphics hardware requires generating a face index list, which is usually done only when the geometry changes.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] Winged-edge meshes are ideally suited for dynamic geometry, such as subdivision surfaces and interactive modelling, since changes to the mesh can occur locally.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] Traversal across the mesh, as might be needed for collision detection, can be accomplished efficiently.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] Winged-edge meshes are not the only representation which allows for dynamic changes to geometry.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] A representation which combines winged-edge meshes and face-vertex meshes is the render dynamic mesh (RDM), which explicitly stores both, the vertices of a face and faces of a vertex (like FV meshes), and the faces and vertices of an edge (like winged-edge).
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] RDM's require less storage space than standard winged-edge meshes, and can be directly rendered by graphics hardware since the face list contains an index of vertices.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] In addition, traversal from vertex to face is explicit (constant time), as is from face to vertex.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] RDM's do not require the four outgoing edges since these can be found by traversing from edge to face, then face to neighboring edge.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] RDM's benefit from the features of winged-edge meshes by allowing for geometry to be dynamically updated.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] See Tobler & Maierhofer (WSCG 2006) for more details.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] The notation *avg(V,V)* means the average number of vertices connected to a given vertex; *avg(E,V)* means the average number of edges connected to a given vertex, and *avg(F,V)* is the average number of faces connected to a given vertex.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] The notation "V → f1, f2, f3, ... → v1, v2, v3, ..." describes that a traversal across multiple elements is required to perform the operation.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] For example, to get "all vertices around a given vertex V" using the face-vertex mesh, it is necessary to first find the faces around the given vertex V using the vertex list.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] Then, from those faces, use the face list to find the vertices around them.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] Winged-edge meshes explicitly store nearly all information, and other operations always traverse to the edge first to get additional info.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] Vertex-vertex meshes are the only representation that explicitly stores the neighboring vertices of a given vertex.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] As the mesh representations become more complex (from left to right in the summary), the amount of information explicitly stored increases.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] This gives more direct, constant time, access to traversal and topology of various elements but at the cost of increased overhead and space in maintaining indices properly.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] As a general rule, face-vertex meshes are used whenever an object must be rendered on graphics hardware that does not change geometry (connectivity), but may deform or morph shape (vertex positions) such as real-time rendering of static or morphing objects.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] Winged-edge or render dynamic meshes are used when the geometry changes, such as in interactive modeling packages or for computing subdivision surfaces.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] Vertex-vertex meshes are ideal for efficient, complex changes in geometry or topology so long as hardware rendering is not of concern.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] Streaming meshes store faces in an ordered, yet independent, way so that the mesh can be transmitted in pieces.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] The order of faces may be spatial, spectral, or based on other properties of the mesh.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] Streaming meshes allow a very large mesh to be rendered even while it is still being loaded.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] Progressive meshes transmit the vertex and face data with increasing levels of detail.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] Unlike *streaming meshes*, progressive meshes give the overall shape of the entire object, but at a low level of detail.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] Additional data, new edges and faces, progressively increase the detail of the mesh.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] Normal meshes transmit progressive changes to a mesh as a set of normal displacements from a base mesh.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] With this technique, a series of textures represent the desired incremental modifications.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] Normal meshes are compact, since only a single scalar value is needed to express displacement.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] However, the technique requires a complex series of transformations to create the displacement textures.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] There exist many different file formats for storing polygon mesh data.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] Each format is most effective when used for the purpose intended by its creator.
[src:mesh-processing/polygon-mesh] Popular formats include .fbx, .dae, .obj, and .stl.
